<TEXT>
secretary of state george p shultz 
indicated tuesday that he and philippine leaders have scored a 
breakthrough in stalled talks on the future of us military bases 
in the philippines 
president corazon aquino said after tuesdays discussions we 
both hope that the talks would be over by the end of this month 
shultz told a news conference im more than ever convinced 
that there is a very strong mutuality of interest in the security 
field and all the reason in the world that somehow well be able to 
work out a continuing partnership a review of the 41yearold 
bases agreement which expires in 1991 has been marked by calls 
from some people for more compensation from the united states and 
by demonstrations against the us military presence 
the review began in april and stalled over the issue of how much 
washington should pay each year for the subic bay naval base clark 
air base and four smaller military installations 
shultz on a 36hour visit to manila met with mrs aquino 
foreign secretary raul manglapus defense secretary fidel v ramos 
and prominent legislators 
he later left for hong kong arriving there wednesday for a 
oneday stay hong kong was the fifth stop on the secretarys 
ninenation asian and pacific tour he earlier visited thailand 
malaysia and indonesia and will proceed after hong kong to china 
south korea japan and the marshall islands 
both the us and filipino sides refused to discuss details of 
the compensation proposals 
house speaker ramon mitra told reporters if the philippine 
side gets favorable conditions i presume this is going to 
register very well among members of the house 
us sources speaking on condition of anonymity said a 
reasonable compromise on the bases could mean increased support by 
washington of manilas war against the 19yearold communist 
insurgency 
under the present accord the united states gives manila 180 
million a year in economic and military aid the bases are the 
largest us military facilities outside the continental united 
states 
manglapus said last april that 12 billion a year was a more 
realistic figure 
shultz said the us military had worked out options in case the 
bases were ousted but the best choice was to stay in the 
philippines 
he said the two sides had perhaps identified some methods that 
might work in reaching a compromise 
shultz also said the philippine military had improved in the 
past two years 
there is a far greater degree of professionalism they are 
better equipped there is a clear mission and a record 
increasingly of success he said 
ramos said shultz promised to expedite the delivery of us 
military equipment to the philippine military the united states 
this year provided more than 85 million in military help 
</TEXT>
