<TEXT>
mostly mozart was mostly marvelous 
the 22nd season of new york citys alliterative summer musical 
festival opened tuesday night with a gala concert featuring not 
one but two superstar soloists american mezzosoprano frederica 
von stade and soviet emigre pianist vladimir feltsman 
both made strong impressions miss von stade sang parto 
parto an aria from mozarts last opera la clemenza di tito 
and both of cherubinos arias from le nozze di figaro she 
sounded at ease in all three her tone aristocratic yet free and 
unaffected her technique was flawless in the difficult runs of the 
first selection with only a hint of strain in the highest part of 
her register 
cherubino is perhaps miss von stades most famous role on stage 
and she demonstrated why communicating the restless energy of a 
lovesick young boy with simple directness 
feltsman who arrived in this country just last year provided 
an elegant performance of mozarts last piano concerto no 27 in 
bflat major this work written less than a year before the 
composer died strikes a mood of serenity and triumph with little 
of the turmoil and tragedy that mark the concertos preceding it 
feltsman played with grace and clarity 
ironically the least satisfying selection of the night was a 
collaboration between the two the concert aria for soprano piano 
and orchestra chio mi scordi di te which mozart wrote for an 
18yearold english singer with whom he had fallen in love 
what sets this difficult aria apart is the intricate interplay 
between the female voice and the piano each seeming to address the 
other in long loving phrases miss von stade and feltsman missed 
the emotional spark and too often seemed to be going through their 
paces rather than communicating 
the opening program which is being repeated tonight and 
televised live on the public broadcasting service was true to the 
title mostly mozart but with a little something else thrown in 
conductor gerard schwartz led a spirited performance of haydns 
grand and humorous symphony no 100 known as the military 
symphony the concert opened with the overture to mozarts opera 
die entfuhrung aus dem serail 
it all went to show once again that mozart who died in poverty 
in vienna at the age of 35 left behind a unique and inexhaustible 
supply of musical riches what other composer could serve as the 
mainstay of a music festival that puts on concerts for seven weeks 
year after year 
highlights of the current season performed in lincoln centers 
avery fisher hall include mozarts rarely heard early opera 
lucia silla haydns lord nelson mass and a chamber 
concert devoted entirely to schubert 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

