dukakis and his top adviser paul brountas met at dukakis 
house monday morning brountas then traveled to washington to meet 
with jackson who said for the first time monday that he would take 
dukakis up on an offer to join the ticket 
jackson told reporters after his meeting with brountas that it 
is selfevident that he wants the job and said he assured 
brountas he would be a loyal vice president 
if it was offered to me i would accept it jackson said he 
has said repeatedly he deserves an offer of the no 2 spot but up 
until monday he had declined to say publicly what his answer would 
be if that offer were extended 
brountas said the two had an excellent meetingvery 
productive but declined to provide any details of the discussion 
afterward he flew back to boston for a latenight meeting with 
dukakis 
after a 45minute session at dukakis home with campaign 
manager susan estrich in attendance brountas was asked if a 
decision had been made 
no comment he said 
asked if the selection process was over brountas responded 
he dukakis can always ask more questions if he wants 
dukakis is expected to announce his choice this week before 
heading to the democratic national convention which opens next 
monday some aides said an announcement could come as soon at 
tuesday but others said there was still no timetable 
although the massachusetts governor faces a budget crisis at 
home that threatens to hurt his national candidacy he arrived at 
