<TEXT>
the united states should raise gasoline taxes 
by 50 cents a gallon require cars to get 45 miles per gallon and 
boost the gasguzzler tax to raise money for rebates to buyers of 
fuelefficient cars an organization of environmentalists 
scientists and business executives said today 
those were central measures in a program outlined by the 
american council for an energyefficient economy that would set a 
national goal of maintaining momentum in improving energy 
efficiency for the rest of the century 
energy efficiency does not require sacrifice the group 
argued in its report we do not advocate saving energy as an end 
in itself it makes sense only when saving energy costs less than 
providing energy including environmental damage and security risks 
in the comparison 
environmental risks of inefficiency are severe the group said 
manmade gases notably carbon dioxide produced by fossil fuels 
threaten to warm the earth by as much as eight degrees fahrenheit 
in the next century raising sea levels and drastically changing 
patterns of rainfall and drought a process some scientists say is 
under way 
increasing the 9centpergallon federal gasoline tax by 10 
cents annually for five years three years if crude oil prices 
double would yield 40 billion to 60 billion a year 
such a tax would help make sure consumers are given a price 
signal that better reflects the real cost of the resource and 
encourages conservation some money could be rebated to the poor 
through income tax provisions 
cars now required to get 26 mpg should get 45 mpg by 2000 
it need not be so that the standards would mean less safety 
from lighter weight if cars are carefully designed the group said 
cars twice as efficient as current models would cost 200 to 
800 more the group estimated the increase would be recouped over 
the life of the car through lower cost of operation 
a stiffer gasguzzler tax which can reach more than 2000 
now but generally applies to only a few luxury cars like jaguar 
would discourage production of highly inefficient cars and provide 
funds more than 11 billion a year in 1994 to encourage 
purchase of gas sippers 
the rebate could be on the order of 1000 for models with 
mileage 50 percent better than todays best implying rebates for 
cars getting about 75 mpg 
energy used per dollar of economic activity declined at a rate 
of about 27 percent per year from 1976 through 1986 and was still 
declining at a 25 percent per year during the economic recovery of 
1983 through 1986 
the 1986 oil price collapse discouraged further gains and the 
decline was only 05 percent in 1987 the energy department says it 
expects gains of about 09 percent a year for the rest of the 
century 
a reasonable international goal would be annual reductions of 2 
percent and we suggest that the united states set an example by 
pursuing a goal of at least 25 percent per year until 2000 the 
group said 
