<TEXT>
drought could have some impact on the nations 
rice crop this year but not in the way heat and dry weather have 
shriveled corn and soybean prospects according to agriculture 
department analysts 
the us rice harvest is all from irrigated land says nathan 
childs of the departments economic research service but that 
doesnt necessarily mean rice is drought proof 
much will depend on how the heat affects rice plants and on 
irrigation practices including reduced yields from rising water 
costs he said monday 
but generally the drought is not expected to chew deeply into 
rice this year at least not like youre seeing in the other 
commodities childs said 
according to usda projections as of june 9 the us rice 
harvest this year could be around 157 million hundredweight up 
nearly a fourth from 1277 million in 1987 
total rice use also is growing says the departments economic 
research service in its latest outlook report and this growth is 
expected to continue in 198889 overall rice demand has increased 
by 20 million hundredweight in the last four years 
greater consumer preference for grainbased foods aggressive 
marketing by rice industry organizations and processors and wider 
availability of easytoprepare rice products have helped raise 
consumption the report said growth in the asian and hispanic 
segment of the us population and increasing popularity of spanish 
and oriental foods among all americans have also helped expand 
consumption 
another growth has been in the amount of rice used to make beer 
an estimated 17 million hundredweight this year up from less 
than 14 million in 198485 
brewers use makes up about 20 percent of total domestic 
consumption and continues to show yeartoyear increases the 
report said anheuserbusch the largest us brewery uses rice 
exclusively s an adjunct in several of its products gains in 
market share by this company over the past several years have 
helped increase rice use in beer even though growth in total beer 
consumption has slowed 
in all domestic rice use may be about 835 million 
hundredweight in 198889 up from 808 million in 198788 and 763 
million in 198687 
rice exports are forecast at 77 million hundredweight up from 
70 million last year but down from 854 million in 198687 
assuming normal weather in major rice exporting countries 
export competition likely will be intense the report said 
expectations of smaller rice supplies in 198788 triggered rice 
price increases and in early 1988 us cash prices were 
substantially higher than world prices however those eased when 
major importers spurned the higherpriced us rice 
also expectations of increased exports from thailand further 
weakened world prices the report added assuming normal 
weather world production will increased in 198889 and keep prices 
below the level of 198788 
for us producers rice prices may be in the range of 5 to 7 
per hundredweight down from 7 to 725 in 198788 but above the 
average of 375 in 198687 the report said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a recent survey by the american association of 
crop insurers shows that more than 370000 farmers bought 
multipleperil crop insurance this year a 19 percent increase from 
1987 
considering that most of these producers acted before there 
was evidence of a drought indicates that the crop insurance program 
is taking hold in the farm country as a riskmanagement tool 
said e eugene gantz executive vice president of the association 
the signup deadline in most areas was april 15 well before the 
severe drought conditions set in he said 
gantz said preliminary estimates show 65 million to 70 million 
acres will likely be protected by crop insurance this year 
compared with 62 million in 1987 the face value of protection of 
insurance written in 1987 was more than 6 billion and probably 
will increase this year he said 
these are producers who didnt want to wait for the federal 
government to come along with a handout gantz said in his 
report they acted in a businesslike manner to protect their own 
farms and their own families from possible disaster 
the multipleperil crop insurance program began seven years ago 
and includes commercial companies that are reinsured against 
catastrophic losses by the federal crop insurance program an 
agency of the agriculture department the fcic also handles 
insurance directly through master marketers who account for about 
20 percent of the total 
gantz said the fcic has indicated there will be no program 
changes in 1989 for most crops beginning with those that will be 
planted this fall 
