<TEXT>
the black box recorders from the downed 
iranian jetliner in the persian gulf should be recoverable 
clearing up questions about the planes flight path and whether its 
pilots received radio warnings us aviation experts say 
several us aviation experts speaking monday on condition that 
they not be identified by name speculated that the recorders 
likely survived the crash unless the missile from the uss vincennes 
hit directly where they were located in the rear of the aircraft 
and although the commander of the iranian navy denied the 
recorders had been found a published report from dubai in the 
united arab emirates quoted unidentified salvage experts as saying 
that the socalled black boxes had been recovered from the gulf 
waters 
all commercial jetliners are required to have the recorders one 
that monitors cockpit conversation and another that tracks 
operations of the plane 
they are housed in separate boxes that actually are painted 
orange but often become blackened by fire in airline crashes they 
are located in the tail section of the plane and designed to 
withstand severe impacts 
the iran air airbus a300 shot down by the vincennes on july 3 
killing all 290 people aboard was believed to have been equipped 
with a sophisticated digital flight recorder that would provide a 
broad range of operating information as well as a cockpit voice 
recorder 
if they are found in good condition and were properly maintained 
by the iranians the recorders could provide a wealth of 
information to investigators including a detailed reproduction of 
the planes flight path from the time of takeoff the experts said 
the cockpit voice recorder which monitors radio communications 
and cockpit conversation on a continuous 30minute loop would 
indicate whether the iran air pilots received repeated radio 
warnings as maintained by the pentagon 
the cockpit tape would be expected to cover the entire flight of 
the iranian jetliner as well as the period during which the plane 
was taxiing and awaiting takeoff at bandar abbas in iran for the 
short trip across the gulf to dubai 
in addition to radio communications the cockpit tape would 
reveal conversation within the cockpit and indicate whether the 
pilots might have intended anything other than a routine flight and 
whether they might have been distracted by mechanical or other 
problems causing them to fly off course or fail to acknowledge 
radio warnings the experts suggested 
the flight data recorder in the a300 is a sophisticated digital 
version that provides more than 80 measures involving the planes 
flight operations including altitude heading air speed and 
whether the plane was experiencing any flight difficulties 
the pentagon has said that the commercial jetliner was perceived 
in part as a threat to the vincennes because of the planes unusual 
flight path and speed officials said the jetliner was descending 
traveling faster than normal for a commercial airliner and heading 
directly toward the us ship there also have been discrepancies 
as to how far the a300 was off from its intended flight path 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

