<TEXT>
president reagans selection of richard l 
thornburgh as his next attorney general marks a return for the 
toughminded former pennsylvania governor to the law enforcement 
roots that first propelled him into the public eye in 1969 
reagan said today that he had chosen thornburgh to replace edwin 
meese iii who announced last week that he would resign by early 
august 
former members of thornburghs gubernatorial administration were 
quick to point out his reputation for integrity and that he 
eliminated the corruption that tainted the tenure of his 
predecessor democrat milton shapp 
they also noted the close ties thornburgh has kept with the 
reagan administration 
as governor thornburgh 55 frequently testified on capitol 
hill on behalf of the presidents proposal for lineitem veto power 
and a constitutional amendment to balance the budget he has turned 
down offers to head the fbi and agency for international 
development and was considered for the health and human services 
cabinet post in 1985 
as governor thornburgh said his budget proposals held spending 
increases to less than the rate of inflation for eight straight 
years he championed a controversial welfare reform law that 
limited cash benefits to three months a year for an estimated 
68000 people considered ablebodied 
but it was his abilities as a prosecutor that first won him 
headlines he was appointed us attorney for western pennsylvania 
in 1969 his attacks on organized crime drug trafficking and 
pornography led to his being appointed assistant attorney general 
in charge of the justice departments criminal division by 
president ford in 1975 
in fact for the first few hours of jimmy carters 
administration he was the highestranking person at the justice 
department said gwen king who left a post as head of 
thornburghs washington office to become a deputy assistant at the 
white house 
hes certainly someone whose integrity is beyond question 
she said before his appointment was confirmed he could bring 
stability and integrity to the position without any doubt and 
frankly i think the administration would be wellserved to ask 
him 
democratic critics said thornburgh lacked compassion and were 
fond of reciting a story of a poor women who began badgering the 
governor during a campaign swing in erie county in 1982 things 
are tough all over thornburgh told the woman 
but his supporters describe thornburgh as methodical and cool 
under pressure 
all of us who worked for him always viewed him as a person who 
weighed things so carefully and was so methodical and precise that 
he would be perfect as attorney general said shirley dennis the 
pennsylvania secretary of community affairs under thornburgh who 
now heads the womens bureau at the us department of labor 
barred by law from seeking a third term as governor thornburgh 
left pennsylvania at the end of 1986 to head the institute of 
politics at harvard universitys kennedy school of government but 
he hardly retreated from the public eye 
rather thornburgh was busier than ever on the political circuit 
back home leading observers to believe his stint at harvard may 
have only been a break between campaigns of one sort or another 
thornburgh has been said to be considering running for governor 
again when democrat robert casey comes up for reelection in 1990 
he also had been mentioned as a possible running mate for george 
bush 
hes a politician his longtime aide david runkel said in a 
telephone interview he has not closed the door on another 
campaign for something 
thornburghs recent activity has included two fundraisers that 
have netted about 100000 for the governor thornburgh 
committee an account he uses to support his travels on behalf of 
other candidates runkel said 
in addition thornburgh is cochairman of pennsylvanias 
victory 88 a federal fund that distributes money for phone 
banks and other republican campaign efforts 
the possibility of a bushthornburgh ticket excited 
pennsylvanias republican convention delegates many of whom named 
the former governor as their top choice for the second spot on the 
ticket 
in 1960 an automobile accident killed thornburghs wife and 
left his youngest son braindamaged he was married again in 1963 
to schoolteacher ginny judson 
