<TEXT>
the nations cities encumbered by burgeoning 
budget gaps spawned by federal aid cutbacks sharply increased 
local fees this fiscal year and many also raised property taxes a 
study reported tuesday 
over half the countrys major cities face potential deficits 
although some will be able to dip into reserves to avoid finishing 
the year in the red said the study by the national league of 
cities 
the present trends are dangerous and potentially 
devastating said alan beals executive director of the league a 
national organization of local governments beals called the 
nations domestic policies on cities indifferent at best and 
destructive at worst 
the league report titled city fiscal conditions in 1988 
describes how 347 communities from large cities such as los 
angeles to smaller towns like yankton sd are coping with the 
end two years ago of the federal revenue sharing program 
the survey found that 67 percent increased existing fees and 
charges for city services in the 1988 fiscal year while 44 percent 
reduced spending this year on capital construction projects 
fiftyfive percent cut back the growth of their operating budgets 
and 41 percent raised property taxes 
those figures were higher than 1987 when 58 percent raised fees 
and 38 percent raised property taxes over the year before 
in addition 37 percent of the cities said they had instituted 
new fees another 14 percent reduced city services 
cities overwhelmingly cited federal cutbacks as the reason for 
their budgetary straits almost half of the cities that cut 
services said less federal money was the main reason and 64 
percent of those who scaled back capital projects cited the loss of 
revenue sharing 
the backbone of america our cities and towns is bending 
under an increasing load beals said at a news conference 
whether this burden will continue to grow more cumbersome or 
whether it will be relieved through a more responsible set of 
national policies is one of the urgent questions of the 1988 
elections and for the next administration beals said at a news 
conference on the report 
the news conference was held as word came that michael dukakis 
the likely democratic presidential nominee had picked sen lloyd 
bentsen of texas as his running mate bentsen heads the senate 
finance committee and has worked with the league on a number of 
issues affecting the nations cities beals noted 
we found him to be very openminded and responsive and he 
has given us a very sympathetic hearing beals said 
the report measured spending estimates for the 1988 fiscal year 
the 12month period that ended june 30 which the report 
acknowledged are not yet final 
it said 50 percent of the cities expect expenditures to exceed 
revenues in 1988 but noted that cities usually are pessimistic in 
such projections the actual percentage of cities that finish their 
fiscal years with deficits is expected to be lower since 
municipalities facing shortfalls dip into reserves carried over 
from previous years to balance their budgets the report said in 
1987 33 percent of the cities surveyed by the league actually 
reported shortfalls down from 40 percent in 1986 
more than half those cities had surpluses in 1986 and 1987 but 
only 24 percent said they expect to take in more than they spend in 
the 1988 fiscal year 
the survey also found that 25 percent of the cities had actually 
seen revenues from all sources decline in 1988 from last year 
in other areas of spending the survey found that 25 percent of 
the cities had reduced the number of city workers 24 percent had 
raised or imposed new fees for developers and 22 percent had frozen 
municipal hiring eighteen percent had instituted new taxes or 
raised sales taxes 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

