<TEXT>
ambassador richard melton who was ordered by 
the nicaraguan government to leave the country is believed to be 
the fifth us diplomat of his rank to be withdrawn at the request 
of the host government over the past 15 years 
earlier this year the us ambassador to saudi arabia hume 
horan was recalled by the united states because of personality 
differences with king fahd 
unlike melton however horan was not declared persona non grata 
but saudi authorities made clear the monarchs displeasure with 
horan who spent only seven months in saudi arabia 
within days after horans recall president reagan nominated 
ambassador walter cutler to replace him 
the case involving melton is believed to be the first of its 
kind since 1976 when the us ambassador to equatorial guinea 
herbert spiro was ordered out of the country us relations with 
equatorial guinea were poor at the time because of unpredictable 
behavior of president masie nguema and other factors 
during that period spiro was the accredited ambassador to both 
cameroon and equatorial guinea but resided in cameroon he made 
occasional visits to equatorial guinea full relations with that 
country were not restored until 1979 
in 1975 the us ambassador to zaire dean hinton was expelled 
by president mobutu sese seko for alleged interference in zaires 
internal affairs 
in 1973 jamaican prime minister michael manley expelled 
ambassador vincent deroulet after the envoy had said the united 
states refrained from interfering in the 1972 national elections in 
jamaica in return for a promise from manley not to nationalize 
certain us business investments in jamaica manley denied the 
allegation 
