<TEXT>
sen lloyd bentsen selected by michael 
dukakis on tuesday as his democratic running mate will also 
continue his bid for a fourth term in the senate a dual campaign 
made legal in texas in 1959 to let lyndon b johnson run two races 
it worked for johnson after losing the 1960 democratic 
presidential nomination to john f kennedy johnson was elected 
vice president and won his senate race 
but johnsons wins cost democrats the senate seat republican 
john tower later won a special election for the post which is 
still held by the gop 
if bentsen wins both races this year his senate seat would 
become vacant in january texas gov bill clements a republican 
would then appoint a replacement to serve until a special election 
clements also would set the special election day under state 
law that election could be on may 7 aug 13 or nov 12 secretary 
of state jack rains said clements also could set an emergency 
election on any date he chooses but that move would have to be 
cleared by the justice department 
rains said it usually takes 70 days to get justice department 
approval for emergency elections 
he also said the law is silent on any deadline for calling 
the special election clements could wait as long as he pleased to 
set it according to rains 
bentsens november senate opponent is us rep beau boulter of 
amarillo who has said it would not be fair for bentsen to make 
both races but david weeks spokesman for the bentsen senate 
campaign said that is just what bentsen will do 
he is going to run a vigorous campaign for the senate weeks 
said 
if he beats boulter and also wins the vice presidency bentsens 
senate seat would be vacant sometime in january he could choose to 
take the senate oath on jan 3 and then resign his senate seat when 
he takes the vice presidential oath on jan 20 bentsen could also 
opt to skip the senate oath in which case the senate seat would be 
open jan 3 
the special senate election would be open to all candidates the 
