us and vietnamese officials will meet 
thursday and friday in hanoi to plan the move to the united states 
of thousands of vietnamese detained after the indochina war because 
of their american connections it was announced tuesday 
the two governments have agreed to the talks to discuss the 
resettlement in the united states of vietnamese reeducation camp 
detainees who wish to come state department spokeswoman phyllis 
oakley told reporters 
the great majority of current and former reeducation camp 
detainees were incarcerated because of their close association with 
the united states and as allies during the war mrs oakley told 
reporters for this compelling humanitarian reason we have 
repeatedly affirmed our strong humanitarian desire to resettle 
those who wish in the united states as soon as possible 
robert l sunseth senior deputy assistant secretary of state 
for refugee programs will head the us delegation to hanoi she 
said 
the state department has estimated that 900000 former employees 
of the us government in south vietnam and officials of the 
defeated saigon government were sent to political reeducation 
camps after the fall of saigon and unification of the country in 
1975 
