weather conditions have been favorable for a 
bumper grain harvest in the soviet union in contrast to damage 
done by heat and drought to us crops a report by the agriculture 
department showed tuesday 
precipitation was above normal in most of the soviet unions 
european area the report said and more than twice the amount of 
normal rain soaked crops in many of the other grain areas 
thus the report said total soviet grain production this year 
continues to be forecast at 215 million metric tons the report 
said that would be the third year in a row that soviet harvests 
have exceeded 200 million tons an unprecedented string of bumper 
yields 
it also would be the third largest soviet grain harvest 
exceeded by the record crop of 2374 million tons in 1978 and the 
1976 harverst of 2238 million tons 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and is equal to 366 bushels 
of wheat or 394 bushels of corn as examples 
despite the bumper harvest the soviet union continues to import 
grain to help rebuild stockpiles and to make more available for an 
expanding livestock sector 
in a related announcement the usda said the soviets have bought 
an additional 350000 tons of us corn for delivery this year 
under a longterm supply agreement between the two countries that 
would be about 138 million bushels 
corn prices have been averaging about 276 per bushel at the 
farm level meaning that the sale could have a farm value of around 
38 million 
the corn is part of the grain the soviet union is committed to 
buy during the fifth and final year of the agreement which calls 
for the annual purchase of at least 9 million tons of us grain 
the pact expires sept 30 and there have been negotiations for a 
new one 
