<TEXT>
fewer than a dozen politicians are among the 
delegates to the 1988 democratic national convention the partys 
biggest political event 
at least thats how many own up to being politicians 
an associated pess survey of more than 3200 of the 4161 
delegates to the convention found that while nearly 1000 of them 
hold elected offices including hundreds of members of congress 
and dozens of governors and mayors only a handful list their 
occupation as politician 
to be exact there are nine of them 
they join nearly 300 lawyers 100 retired people an actor a 
cook and a casket manufacturer this week as they cram into the 
cramped auditorium of the omni to nominate massachusetts gov 
michael dukakis for president 
of the delegates who hail from all 50 states the district of 
columbia and five us territories the typical conventiongoer 
is white middleaged and collegeeducated almost twothirds of 
them have not been delegates before the ap survey found 
their average age is 47 some 67 percent went to college and 69 
percent are white twentyone percent are black and almost 5 
percent are hispanic 
under democratic party rules the delegate seats are divided 
equally among men and women and while there are no firm quotas 
state parties were encouraged to recruit enough minorities so the 
racial mix of the delegation roughly parallels that of the states 
democratic voters 
still there was some irritation at the partys affirmative 
action program 
we went from unfair to more unfair said morton povman a 
dukakis delegate from new york under the rules a person can get 
the most votes and be elected by the people and yet not be selected 
as a delegate not because dukakis doesnt want you but because if 
youre a white catholic and they have enough white catholics 
theyll pick a black whatever 
while no floor fights are expected over the presidential 
nomination credentials challenges or changes to the rules the 
delegates come to town with a lot weighing on their minds 
a sampling of those surveyed by the ap found that about a third 
of them are worried about the federal budget deficit unemployment 
foreign trade or the economy in general next on the list is 
combatting the flow of illegal drugs into the united states 
followed by education and the twin issues of world peace and 
