<TEXT>
a year ago the british massmarket jeweler 
ratners group plc spent about 200 million to acquire an ohiobased 
jewelry company 
the experience was so positive the transaction so simple and 
the rewards potentially so great that ratners since has snapped up 
two more us companies 
ratners embodies a veritable 10year tradition among the 
british who are the most prolific acquirers of us businesses 
followed by the canadians west germans french and japanese 
those expecting to see a slowdown tied to the dollars recent 
resurgence in foreignexchange trading may be disappointed like a 
tycoon buying a fine diamond for his mistress corporate suitors 
from abroad still act as if money is no object at least not now 
last year foreigners spent 404 billion on us acquisitions 
in the first six months of this year the tally registered 21 
billion by some estimates 
those involved in the deals from investment bankers to the 
purchasers themselves say the status of the us currency is of 
little consequence as long as it doesnt really skyrocket 
its a commercial strategy not the exchange rate thats going 
to influence us said andrew coppel ratners group finance 
director from his london office 
since its long decline bottomed out recently the dollars value 
has risen as much as 10 percent against some major currencies most 
foreign companies with us operations are active participants in 
the currency markets buying and selling dollars as a hedge against 
swings in the exchange rate 
wt grimm amp co a chicagobased firm that tracks mergers and 
acquisitions noted that foreigners often end up paying even more 
for us companies than american acquirers 
while grimm attributed that to their aggressive entry into the 
us market investment bankers look to more practical 
considerations for one thing youve got a lengthier process of 
negotiating a contract simply because you must bring all your 
troops from your home country and theyre not familiar with the 
process said les fabuss a senior vice president at shearson 
lehman hutton inc 
in addition foreigners often do not initiate their own 
exclusive transactions 
its hard for them to say i want company x and go out and 
try to get it they tend to appear in auction situations where the 
highest price wins and currency allows them to pay slightly 
more he added 
last year foreign buyers announced 220 takeover deals 
accounting for 11 percent of all the mergers and acquisitions in 
the united states grimm reported 
nearly half of those deals carried price tags of 100 million or 
more with the average price of a us company totaling a record 
3154 millionmost of the takeovers occurred in the retail 
chemicals and industrial equipment and machinery categories 
among the billiondollar deals so far this year are the british 
construction company beazer plcs purchase of koppers inc and 
canadian investor robert campeaus acquisition of federated 
department stores inc 
currently under way is the sale of at least a dozen units of the 
singer co to help finance florida investor paul bilzerians 
purchase of the machinery and defense company a number of 
foreigners are bidding on those operations 
despite their willingness to pay top dollar for us properties 
foreigners are still finding some relative bargains here the labor 
department said american factories outperformed their rivals 
overseas last year in reducing labor costs and making their goods 
more competitive on world markets 
measured in devalued american dollars labor costs in the united 
states declined 15 percent in 1987 compared with increases of 75 
percent in south korea 77 percent in canada 135 pzss an economist 
with data resources inc of 
lexington mass 
finding an american mate takes some looking coppel said ratners 
began assessing the us market in september 1986 and quickly 
realized the enormous potential of the 20 billionayear 
jewelry market 
with the help of painewebber inc ratners zeroed in on sterling 
inc headquartered in akron ohio the deal closed less than a 
year later 
of particular interest to ratners was sterlings diamond 
expertise savvy in buying raw gemstones in tel aviv bombay and 
the netherlands sterling has shown ratners how to cut costs so 
much that coppel predicted the companys diamond business would 
jump from 12 percent to 20 percent of total sales 
since then weve been able to acquire two other companies at a 
much more favorable exchange rate coppel said referring to 
the privately held jewelers osterman inc of toledo and westhall 
inc in akron 
george c lodge a professor at harvard universitys business 
school said that the type of company helps determine the price 
foreigners are willing to pay 
if youre coming here to acquire the latest american 
technology in genesplitting the dollar rate is not as important 
because intellectual assets are harder to value he said on the 
other hand if you are coming here to set up an auto factory then 
the exchange rate becomes more important 
political pressure has kept the technologically aggressive 
japanese from bidding on american hightech companies but politics 
may also be contributing to the foreign merger wave 
as the politics of trade become more intense japanese and 
european companies regard a holding in the us as a protector of 
their access to our marketplace lodge said 
as the flow of business across the oceans increases investment 
banking companies have responded by paying more attention to 
courting overseas clients over the past year shearson has opened 
fullservice offices in west germany and france rather than 
relying on small branches 
merrill lynch amp co is looking east for growth employment in 
the companys tokyo office has jumped to 400 from 290 less than two 
years ago in addition the company has established a japan 
group in new york to facilitate transactions between us and 
japanese businesses a spokesman said 
at chase manhattan bank a new unit was established in april 
specifically to work on foreign direct investment in the united 
states the operations 20member staff currently has several 
major deals in the works said bank spokesman ken mills 
while foreigners are reveling in all the dollars their 
currencies can buy some of the americans doing business with them 
arent so happy one investment banker on a recent business trip in 
paris complained that his 435anight room at the elegant hotel le 
crillon was a mere broom closet 
lamenting how few francs his dollar buys he said why is it 
california chardonnays now make sense 
