<DOCNO> AP880712-0297 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
honesty and fairness will be in the curriculum at 
harvard business school starting this fall when all students 
entering the graduate school will be required to take a threeweek 
course in ethics 
after the wall street insider trading scandal broke in 1986 the 
nations business schools harvard included were criticized for 
not stressing ethics in their teachings of future business managers 
we want to send a signal early on that these issues are 
important to the organization thomas piper one of the 
professors who will teach the course at harvard said in tuesdays 
editions of the boston globe 
piper defined the teaching of ethics as instilling the values of 
respect honesty trust and fairness and said the key was to show 
that ethics are part of the decisionmaking process for managers 
the ungraded course will begin the second week of the term the 
school also plans to have more discussion of ethics in its regular 
courses and has hired research assistants to develop material 
workshops will be held for faculty members 
fewer than 10 percent of business schools require students to 
take ethics according to ethics specialist michael hoffman of 
bentley college 
last year harvard received 20 million from former securities 
and exchange commission chairman john shad for the teaching of 
ethics 
harvards critics including some faculty members had 
questioned the schools commitment to teaching ethics some critics 
suggested at the time of shads gift that harvard got interested in 
the subject only when it got the money 
the school countered that ethics already were taught in many of 
its regular courses and a separate course was not needed 
piper told the globe that after one year of study harvard 
decided on a dual approach a separate minicourse and more 
discussion of ethics in other courses 
he said ethics always had been taught at harvard but may have 
been squeezed out over time interest in doing more came before the 
wall street scandal he said but the scandal made people realize 
that the pendulum may have swung too far 
last year harvard university president derek bok told the globe 
he did not think professors at the business school are able to 
put ethics into their courses at the level they should 
there is a dangerous tendency on the part of some people to 
say that ethics is something we all know about bok said 
</TEXT>
